# flotilla private WARNLIST — TEMPLATE (advisory domain-vocabulary tier)
#
# Copy this file to  .flotilla/private-warnlist  (which is gitignored) and fill it
# with the DOMAIN VOCABULARY of YOUR deployment — the jargon that, embedded in free
# text or an example name, would deanonymize your fleet even when no hard identifier
# is present. The boundary guard (scripts/check-private-boundary.sh) and the runtime
# firewall read it and, on a hit, WARN — they NEVER refuse, suppress, or fail CI on
# it. In CI, provide the same content via the FLOTILLA_PRIVATE_WARNLIST repo secret
# instead, so your vocabulary is never committed.
#
# WARNLIST vs DENYLIST — two distinct tiers:
#   - private-denylist  → a hit is FAIL-CLOSED: refused (runtime) / CI exit 1. Use it
#     for UNAMBIGUOUS identifiers (your real desk/org/broker names, account shapes).
#   - private-warnlist  → a hit is ADVISORY: warn + still publish (runtime) / WARN
#     section + CI exit 0. Use it for AMBIGUOUS domain vocabulary that is too
#     false-positive-prone to fail-close on but is worth a human look.
#
# Why an advisory tier exists: an identifier scan misses a deployment's domain words
# woven into ordinary prose or an example/branch name. Those words are high-signal
# but high-false-positive, so they earn a human glance, not a hard block. A human
# adjudicates each WARN.
#
# One term or PCRE regex per line (the guard matches with `grep -P`; the Go firewall
# matches with RE2 — keep terms to the RE2-compatible subset so the two engines agree,
# which the conformance test enforces). Blank lines and #-comments ignored.
#
# The lines below are ILLUSTRATIVE placeholders — replace them with your own.

# --- your domain's jargon (single words or short phrases that name your domain) ---
your-domain-jargon-term
your-other-jargon-term

# --- your domain's product / instrument / artifact names ---
YourDomainArtifactName

# --- multi-spelling vocabulary (a PCRE alternation on one line) ---
# (foo[- ]?bar|baz[- ]?qux)
